content.text:
Magic address is `findajx@gmail.com`. Here's a copy-paste confirmation protocol — **no code changes**, run entirely from the background console. It will tell us *which* of the mechanisms is actually firing.

## Step 0 — Open the background console
`chrome://extensions` → enable Developer mode → find **Auxilio Visitor** → click **"Inspect views: service worker"**. That opens DevTools for the background worker (distinct from the side-panel and page consoles — make sure it's this one). Keep it open.

## Step 1 — Snapshot the current tracked set
Create your visitor event first, then paste this into the background console:

```js
chrome.storage.local.get([
  'auxilio.markedEvents','auxilio.syncToken','auxilio.handledEvents',
  'auxilio.engineHandled','auxilio.lastFullSync'
]).then(r => {
  const marked = r['auxilio.markedEvents'] || {};
  console.log('marked count:', Object.keys(marked).length);
  console.table(Object.values(marked).map(m => ({ title: m.title, start: m.start, eventId: m.eventId, iCalUid: m.iCalUid })));
  console.log('hasSyncToken?', !!r['auxilio.syncToken'],
              '| handled:', r['auxilio.handledEvents'],
              '| engineHandled:', r['auxilio.engineHandled'],
              '| lastFullSync:', r['auxilio.lastFullSync'] && new Date(r['auxilio.lastFullSync']).toLocaleString());
});
```

Note whether your event is in the table, and whether it shows under `handled` / `engineHandled`.

## Step 2 — The wipe test (the regression itself)
Reload the extension (`chrome://extensions` → the reload ↻ icon on the card). The worker restarts, so **reopen** "Inspect views: service worker". In the fresh console, look for:

```
[auxilio] sync done { mode: "full", magicAddress: "findajx@gmail.com", itemsReturned: …, markedTotal: …, newMarked: … }
```

(If nothing logs, the worker is idle — focus the Calendar tab or open the side panel to trigger a sync.) Then **re-run the Step 1 snippet**.

- **Event was in `marked` before the reload, gone after** → wipe-on-reload confirmed.
- Also watch for any `[auxilio] sync MISS: magic address in payload but isMarked() is false` — that's the attendee-trim signature.

## Step 3 — The smoking gun: what `events.list` actually returns
This calls the Calendar API exactly like the full re-scan does (`timeMin=now`), then again with a wider window, so we can see *why* the rebuild misses it:

```js
(async () => {
  const MAGIC = 'findajx@gmail.com';
  const r = await chrome.storage.session.get('auxilio.tokens');
  const tok = r['auxilio.tokens'];
  if (!tok) { console.warn('No cached token — open the side panel / sign in first, then retry.'); return; }
  const run = async (label, timeMin) => {
    const url = new URL('https://www.googleapis.com/calendar/v3/calendars/primary/events');
    url.searchParams.set('singleEvents','true');
    url.searchParams.set('maxResults','250');
    url.searchParams.set('timeMin', timeMin);
    url.searchParams.set('fields','items(id,iCalUID,summary,status,start,attendees(email,resource))');
    const res = await fetch(url, { headers: { Authorization: `Bearer ${tok.accessToken}` } });
    const items = (await res.json()).items || [];
    console.log(`\n=== ${label} — ${items.length} events ===`);
    console.table(items.map(e => ({
      title: e.summary,
      start: e.start && (e.start.dateTime || e.start.date),
      hasMagic: (e.attendees||[]).some(a => (a.email||'').toLowerCase() === MAGIC),
      attendees: (e.attendees||[]).map(a=>a.email).join(', ')
    })));
  };
  const now = new Date();
  const startOfToday = new Date(now.getFullYear(), now.getMonth(), now.getDate()).toISOString();
  await run(`FULL RE-SCAN WINDOW (timeMin=now=${now.toISOString()})`, now.toISOString());
  await run(`WIDER WINDOW (timeMin=startOfToday=${startOfToday})`, startOfToday);
})();
```

## How to read it

| What you see | Conclusion | Fix it points to |
|---|---|---|
| Event present in **wider** window but **absent** in the `timeMin=now` window | `timeMin=now` excludes it (already started / all-day today) | **F2** (widen window) + **F1** (don't wipe) |
| Event present in both but **`hasMagic: false`** | Google trimmed the magic attendee out of `events.list` | **F3** (events.get fallback) |
| Event present in both with **`hasMagic: true`**, yet Step 2 showed it gone from `marked` after reload | Pure wipe/rebuild timing, or it's being dropped by `handled`/`engineHandled` (check Step 1) | **F1** (merge not wipe); if handled-flagged, the suppression logic |
| Event **absent from both** windows | `events.list` isn't returning it yet (consistency lag, secondary calendar, or not actually saved with the magic attendee) — wait ~30s and re-run Step 3 | not the wipe — a capture/lag issue |

Paste back the `[auxilio] sync done` line from Step 2 and the two tables from Step 3 (titles can be redacted — I mainly need `start`, `hasMagic`, and which window the event appears in), and I'll tell you definitively which fix to apply.

That output changes the diagnosis — and it **refutes my earlier hypothesis**. Good thing we checked before writing code. Let me be straight about what the data shows:

## My "wipe / timeMin" theory was wrong

- `markedTotal: 1`, and you saw the event in the Step 1 table. **The event IS being captured into `marked`, with its title.** So it's not being destructively wiped, and `timeMin=now` is not excluding it. F1/F2 are *not* the fix. Scratch them.

## What the data actually reveals

The smoking gun is `itemsReturned: 6041` and the Step 3 wall of **250 events all titled "Lunch"**. You have a **daily recurring "Lunch"** event with no end date. `events.list` is called with `singleEvents=true` and **no `timeMax`** (`calendar.ts:185-197`), so Google expands every recurring series into individual instances across the *entire* forward horizon (~2 years). One daily event alone = ~700 instances; your calendar expands to **6,041 items per full scan**.

That's the real problem, and here's how it produces your symptoms:

1. **A full re-scan must paginate all 6,041 items** (25 pages of 250) and only writes `marked` **after the whole loop finishes** (`calendar-sync.ts:236`). That takes many seconds.
2. **`629fae4` triggers a full re-scan on every extension reload** (`clearSyncToken` on `onInstalled`). During dev you reload constantly, so you repeatedly hit a multi-second window where the scan is mid-flight and `marked` is still stale/empty.
3. **MV3 kills idle service workers aggressively** (~30s, 5-min hard cap). A long 25-page fetch loop can be terminated before it writes `marked` — so that scan is abandoned with nothing saved, and the next reload starts over.

So during that window: the homescreen reads an empty/stale `marked` → **"No upcoming visitor events"**; the named nudge (which comes from `marked`) hasn't populated → only the **titleless optimistic DOM nudge** shows; the sent list is empty. Once a scan *does* complete (as one did — hence `markedTotal: 1`), it appears. That intermittency is exactly what you'd feel as "it used to work, now it doesn't" — and `629fae4` made it worse by running the expensive scan on every reload, not because of timeMin.

## The real fix direction

- **G1 — Bound the window with `timeMax`** (e.g. `now + 60–90 days`). Visitor nudges are near-term; this cuts 6,041 → a few hundred, so every scan is 1–2 pages and completes reliably before the worker is killed. **Highest impact.**
- **G2 — Stop full-rescanning on every reload.** Gate `clearSyncToken` on an actual magic-address config change (hash compare), so reloads don't keep re-triggering the expensive scan. (This is the old F4, still valid.)
- **G3 — Make the long scan resilient** (write `marked` progressively per page, or keep the worker alive). Lower priority once G1 shrinks the scan.

## One more empirical check (proves G1 before we build it)

Paste this in the background console — it paginates fully both ways and times them:

```js
(async () => {
  const MAGIC = 'findajx@gmail.com';
  const tok = (await chrome.storage.session.get('auxilio.tokens'))['auxilio.tokens'];
  if (!tok) { console.warn('sign in first'); return; }
  const fetchAll = async (timeMax) => {
    let pageToken, total = 0, pages = 0; const marked = [];
    do {
      const url = new URL('https://www.googleapis.com/calendar/v3/calendars/primary/events');
      url.searchParams.set('singleEvents','true'); url.searchParams.set('maxResults','250');
      url.searchParams.set('timeMin', new Date().toISOString());
      if (timeMax) url.searchParams.set('timeMax', timeMax);
      if (pageToken) url.searchParams.set('pageToken', pageToken);
      url.searchParams.set('fields','items(id,summary,start,attendees(email)),nextPageToken');
      const data = await (await fetch(url,{headers:{Authorization:`Bearer ${tok.accessToken}`}})).json();
      const items = data.items||[]; total += items.length; pages++;
      for (const e of items) if ((e.attendees||[]).some(a=>(a.email||'').toLowerCase()===MAGIC))
        marked.push({title:e.summary, start:e.start&&(e.start.dateTime||e.start.date)});
      pageToken = data.nextPageToken;
    } while (pageToken);
    return { total, pages, marked };
  };
  const plus90 = new Date(Date.now()+90*864e5).toISOString();
  console.time('unbounded'); const a = await fetchAll(null); console.timeEnd('unbounded');
  console.log('UNBOUNDED →', a.total, 'items,', a.pages, 'pages | visitor events:', a.marked);
  console.time('bounded90'); const b = await fetchAll(plus90); console.timeEnd('bounded90');
  console.log('timeMax=now+90d →', b.total, 'items,', b.pages, 'pages | visitor events:', b.marked);
})();
```

I expect the bounded call to drop from ~6,041/25 pages to a few hundred/1–2 pages and run several times faster, while still finding your visitor event. If it does, **G1 + G2** is the fix.

Two quick things to confirm so I know what you're even running:
